  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN152.1-kilavi">iravukkuṟi <app><lem>puṇarntu</lem><rdg wit="#C2 #C3 #RK">vantu</rdg></app> nīṅkun talaimakaṉ taṉ neñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What he who left after having united [with her] in a night tryst said to his heart.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN152.1">
              <l>neñcunaṭuṅ karumpaṭar tīra vantu</l>
              <l>kuṉṟuḻai naṇṇiya cīṟū rāṅkaṭ</l>
              <l>celīiya peyarvōḷ vaṇarcuri yaim<supplied>pā</supplied></l>
              <l>laṇaṅ<supplied>ku</supplied>kō lakavu<supplied>na</supplied>rp puranta pēricaic</l>
              <l>ciṉaṅkeḻu tāṉait tittaṉ veḷiya</l>
              <l>ṉiraṅku<supplied>nīrp</supplied> parappiṟ kāṉalam peruntuṟaik</l>
              <l>kaṉantaru naṉkalañ citaiyat tākkuñ</l>
              <l>ciṟuveḷ ḷiṟaviṉ kuppai yaṉṉa</l>
              <l>vuṟupakai tarūu moymmucu piṇṭa<supplied>ṉ</supplied></l>
              <l>muṉaimura ṇuṭaiyak kaṭanta veṉvē</l>
              <l>licaina<supplied>l lī</supplied>kaik kaḷiṟuvīcu vaṇmaki<supplied>ḻ</supplied>p<anchor n="1"/></l>
              <l>pārattut talaiva<anchor n="2"/> ṉāra naṉ<supplied>ṉa</supplied></l>
              <l>ṉeḻiṉi neṭuvaraip pāḻic cilampiṟ</l>
              <l>kalamayiṟ kalavat taṉṉa tō<supplied>ḷē</supplied></l>
              <l><supplied>valvi liḷai</supplied>yar perumaka ṉaḷḷi</l>
              <l>cōlai yaṭukkattuc curumpuṇa virinta</l>
              <l>kaṭavuṭ kānta ḷuḷḷum palavuṭa</l>
              <l>ṉiṟumpūtu kañaliya <supplied>vā</supplied>ymalar nāṟi</l>
              <l>valliṉum vallā rāyiṉuñ ceṉṟōrkkuc</l>
              <l>cālaviḻ neṭuṅkuḻi niṟaiya vīcu</l>
              <l>mā<supplied>a</supplied>l yāṉai yā<supplied>a</supplied>y kāṉattut</l>
              <l>talaiyāṟṟu nilaiiya cēyuya<supplied>r</supplied> piṟaṅkal</l>
              <l>vēyamaik kaṇṇiṭai purai<supplied>i</supplied>c</l>
              <l>cēya vāyiṉu naṭuṅkutuyar tarumē.</l>

            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>The [hair] waving [and] winding in five parts</l>
                <l>of her, who came to end the difficult affliction [my] heart was shivering with</l>
                <l rend="indent8">[and] turned to go back</l>
                <l>there to the little village situated near the hills, (1-3)</l>
                <l>[and her] shoulders, like the feathers of an ornamental peacock (14)</l>
                <l>from the flank of mount Pāḻi, in the long mountains of Eḻiṉi, (13)</l>
                <l>of sandal[-smeared] Naṉṉaṉ, chief of Pāram, (12)</l>
                <l>with the liberal joy of bestowing elephant bulls as famous gifts, (11)</l>
                <l>with a victorious spear that prevailed so that hostilities on the front broke, (10)</l>
                <l>over Piṇṭaṉ, with the valorous langur, who brought ongoing enmity, (9)</l>
                <l>like the heaps of small white prawn (8)</l>
                <l>that attack, [for them] to be ruined, the good vessels that bring abundance (7)</l>
                <l>to the big harbour with a seashore grove by the expanse of roaring water (6)</l>
                <l>of Tittaṉ Veḷiyaṉ with a furious army (5)</l>
                <l>of great fame that protected singers with tormenting sticks, (4)</l>
                <l>being fragrant with choice blossoms that have become amazingly dense, (18)</l>
                <l>many together, all inside the god’s Malabar lilies (17)</l>
                <l>that unfurled for bees to eat on the forested mountain side (16)</l>
                <l>of Naḷḷi, great man with strong-bowed young warriors, (15)</l>
                <l>resembling the middle [part] of the regular joints of bamboo (23)</l>
                <l>glittering high in the distance where Kalaiyāṟu is established, (22)</l>
                <l>in the forest of Āay with big elephants (21)</l>
                <l>who showers rice from pots so that the large [stomach] pits fill (20)</l>
                <l>of those who have gone [for him], whether they are capable or not, (19)</l>
                <l>they bring shivering misery, even when they are far [from me]. (24)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

